 <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">controlled by the ground electronically adiabatic potential energy surface 
  <span class="italic">V</span>, with μ being the reduced mass of the system and ∇ denoting the Laplacian operator, applying a convergent close-coupling technique. To describe the concerted bond breaking and bond forming taking place in the hydrogen atom transfer reaction, we use hyper-spherical coordinates: the hyperradius, ρ, playing the role of a reaction coordinate being capable to describe democratically both the reactants and products channels, and five angular variables. Alternative parameterizations of the hyperangles have been proposed, see references (Pack and Parker, 
  <a rid="B43" ref-type="bibr" href="#B43">1987</a>; Launay and Le Dourneuf, 
  <a rid="B35" ref-type="bibr" href="#B35">1989</a>; Aquilanti et al., 
  <a rid="B2" ref-type="bibr" href="#B2">2000</a>). The computer code (Skouteris et al., 
  <a rid="B52" ref-type="bibr" href="#B52">2000</a>) used to carry out scattering calculations implements the formalism in Delves hyper-spherical coordinates.
 </p>
 <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">The wave function Ψ is expressed in terms of eigenfunctions of the total angular momentum and internal states of the system. The integration over the angular variables leads to a multichannel scattering problem as a function of ρ</p>
